maps created in Spanish America, Europe, the United States, and Asia, these essays take us from the Aztecs documenting the founding of Tenochtitlan, to early modern Japanese reconstructing nostalgic landscapes before Western encroachments, to nineteenth-century Americans grappling with the new concept of deep time. The book also features a defense of traditional paper maps by digital mapmaker William Rankin. With more than one hundred color maps and illustrations, Time in Maps will draw the attention of anyone interested in cartographic history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aCartographyxHistoryvCongresses. 0aTime in cartographyvCongresses 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  acartography.  aearly modern era.  aenlightenment.  ahistorical maps.  atemporality.  atime.  avisual studies.1 aAkerman, James R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDora, Veronica Della, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMundy, Barbara E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPegg, Richard A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRankin, William, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRosenberg, Daniel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchulten, Susan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSmith Rumsey, Abby, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWigen, Kären, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWigen, Kären, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aWinterer, Caroline, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWinterer, Caroline, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is par